DataFrame

.data structure
.stores and manipulates data in a table format (rows and columns)
    .similar to Excel or SQL
.easens data handling, filtering, and analyzing large datasets 

.creating a DataFrame
    .using a list 
        .it automatically assigns index values to the rows when passing the list 
        .each item in the list becomes a row 
        .DataFrame consists of a single, unnamed columns

    .using a dictionary of Numpy array
        .each key = column name
        .each corresponding Numpy array = values for the column  
    .using list of dictionaries 
        .each dictionary represents a row
        .useful for handling structured data from APIs or JSON
            .commonly used for web scraping and API processing 


dataframe index
.acts as reference for each row in a dataset 
.can be numeric or based on specific column values 
.RangeIndex is usually the default - starts from 0
    .can be customized for better understanding 
.it can be used as an attribute to access the current index of a dataframe 
.easens locating specific data points using the .loc() method 


    .using Powershell:
        .create the dataframe 
        .save it to a .csv file with a false index
        .then read the csv file 

    >> setting custom index
        .use set_index() method 
        .sets the index of the dataframe by setting one or more columns as the new index

        .reset = df.set_index('column_name')


.saving two csv tables in one file
    .save them in an Excel file - to have the files separate 

    with pd.ExcelWriter("combined.xlsx") as writer:
        df1.to_excel(writer, sheet_name="Table1", index=False)
        df2.to_excel(writer, sheet_name="Table2", index=False)

    
Accessing DataFrame
.accessing columns  
    .accessed individually using bracket notation 
    .it retrieves the column as a Series, which can then be further manipulated

.accessing rows by index
    .access specific rows using iloc(for positional indexing) or loc(for label-based indexing)

.accessing multiple rows or columns 
    .pass a list of column names or index positions
    .useful when there is need to select several columns or rows for further analysis 

.accessing rows based on conditions
    .filter rows based on conditions or meeting specific criteria

.accessing specific cells with at and iat
    .for accessing specific cells 
        .at[] method for label-based indexing
        .iat[] method for integer position-based indexing 
    .both methods are optimized for fast access to single values 